{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566408"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:40:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:40:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.07,0.51,0.11,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86229"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70498"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"446"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3751"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41895"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86229"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive fatigue and shortness of breath. She is undergoing R-CHOP chemotherapy for diffuse large B-cell lymphoma and started prophylactic medication for \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii \u003C/em\u003Epneumonia two weeks ago. She has a medical history of severe asthma requiring previous intensive care admission and a severe sulfa allergy. Her regular medications include fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 78 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocytes: 8% (0.5-2.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 450 U/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaptoglobin: \u0026lt;0.1 g/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect antiglobulin test: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood film: numerous bite cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely responsible for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pentamidine","Clindamycin","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole","Atovaquone","Dapsone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with evidence of haemolytic anaemia (low haemoglobin, elevated reticulocytes, elevated lactate dehydrogenase, low haptoglobin) with bite cells on blood film. Bite cells are characteristic of oxidative haemolysis. The negative direct antiglobulin test indicates this is not immune-mediated haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapsone\u003C/strong\u003E is known to cause oxidative haemolysis, particularly in patients with glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency. It is commonly used for \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E pneumonia prophylaxis in patients who cannot tolerate trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and pentamidine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E can cause immune-mediated haemolysis but does not typically cause oxidative haemolysis with bite cells. While it is the first-line agent for \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E pneumonia prophylaxis, it is contraindicated in this patient due to her sulfa allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPentamidine\u003C/strong\u003E nebuliser is an alternative agent for PJP prophylaxis in patients who cannot tolerate first-line prophylaxis. However, it is not associated with oxidative haemolysis. It should be used with caution in patients with severe asthma, due to the risk of bronchospasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtovaquone\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative agent for PJP prophylaxis in patients who cannot tolerate first-line prophylaxis. However, it is not associated with oxidative haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used alone for \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E pneumonia prophylaxis and is not associated with oxidative haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dapsone can cause oxidative haemolysis, particularly in patients with G6PD deficiency","Bite cells on blood film are characteristic of oxidative haemolysis","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is the first-line agent for Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia prophylaxis"],"references":["Luzzatto L, Ally M, Notaro R. Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency. Blood. 2020 Sep 10;136(11):1225\u201340. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32702756/","Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed 2025 Jan 14. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70498","links":{"se